b"In Flanders fields the poppies blow
Between the crosses, row on row,
That mark our place; and in the sky
The larks, still bravely singing, fly
Scarce heard amid the guns below.

We are the Dead. Short days ago
We lived, felt dawn, saw sunset glow,
Loved and were loved, and now we lie
In Flanders fields.

Take up our quarrel with the foe:
To you from failing hands we throw
The torch; be yours to hold it high.
If ye break faith with us who die
We shall not sleep, though poppies grow
In Flanders fields.

:red_heart_selector:

Lieutenant-Colonel John McCrae
~ May 3, 1915 (As published in Punch Magazine, December 8, 1915)
--
Au champ d\xe2\x80\x99honneur, les coquelicots
Sont parseme\xcc\x81s de lot en lot
Aupre\xcc\x80s des croix; et dans l\xe2\x80\x99espace
Les alouettes devenues lasses
Me\xcc\x82lent leurs chants au sifflement
Des obusiers.

Nous sommes morts
Nous qui songions la veille encor'
A\xcc\x80 nos parents, a\xcc\x80 nos amis,
C\xe2\x80\x99est nous qui reposons ici
Au champ d\xe2\x80\x99honneur.

A\xcc\x80 vous jeunes de\xcc\x81sabuse\xcc\x81s
A\xcc\x80 vous de porter l\xe2\x80\x99oriflamme
Et de garder au fond de l\xe2\x80\x99a\xcc\x82me
Le gou\xcc\x82t de vivre en liberte\xcc\x81.

Acceptez le de\xcc\x81fi, sinon
Les coquelicots se faneront
Au champ d\xe2\x80\x99honneur

John McCrae
~ Le 3 mai 1915

:red_heart_selector:
(Adaptation franc\xcc\xa7aise du poe\xcc\x80me In Flanders Fields de John McCrae par Jean Pariseau.)"
